A Go-based payment workflow has been running in production for 8 months. An engineer makes two sequential code changes: first replacing `ActivityA` with `ActivityC` (patched as 'Step1' v1), then later replacing `ActivityC` with `ActivityD` (patched as 'Step1' v2). Some workflows are still on DefaultVersion, some on v1, and some on v2. The engineer now wants to remove the DefaultVersion branch by changing `minSupported` from `workflow.DefaultVersion` to `1`. A workflow execution that ran entirely before the first `GetVersion` call was ever introduced — meaning it has NO marker in its history for 'Step1' — is replayed on this updated code. What happens?

```go
v := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", 1, 2)
if v == 1 {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityC, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityD, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
}
```

An engineering team is using the legacy Go Worker Versioning API (Build ID compatibility sets) on a task queue named `payments-queue`. They have deployed Build ID `v1` as the default. They now run:

```go
err := client.UpdateWorkerBuildIdCompatibility(ctx, &client.UpdateWorkerBuildIdCompatibilityOptions{
   TaskQueue: "payments-queue",
   Operation: &client.BuildIDOpAddNewCompatibleVersion{
      BuildID:                   "v2",
      ExistingCompatibleBuildId: "v1",
   },
})
```

Immediately after, they start a brand-new workflow execution. A child workflow is launched from within a running `v1`-pinned workflow execution, using default `VersioningIntent`. Which workers will receive tasks for the new top-level execution and the child workflow respectively?
